Jed,<br><br>
You must not loose sight of the fact that most of those who fought in Vietnam were the &quot;property&quot; of the United States, and without recourse. Many fought because of patriotism, many fought because they liked combat, and many for other reasons. The fact remains that they fought. Protestors did not face combat. I imagine most enjoyed the creature comforts of home and hearth, interspersed with occasional episodes of demonstration. I do not think many emulated the soldier in Vietnam by eating bad food, going hungry, sleeping in the mud and water, living with bugs, snakes, and rats, getting tropical diseases, and being shot at in a lethal manner. <br><br>
It is consequently very difficult to connect frustration of protestors as manifest by abuse to Vietnam Veterans. I am sensitive to those who protested the war and kept the Vietnam Veteran out of the line of responsibility, and treated them respectfully. <br><br>
I have absolutely no tolerance for those who verbally and physically abused Vietnam Veterans, and committed acts of discrimination. I did my duty as my country required, and any derisive treatment was completely improper. Furthermore, the judgement of Vietnam Veterans combat activities with respect to &quot;civil&quot; standards of conduct is ludicrous.<br><br>
Upon return &quot;home&quot;, I quickly learned the feelings associated with &quot;riding in the back of the bus.&quot; The reception I received from the worthless cretin thugs outside Oakland remains an experience of flashback intensity. The meals I was refused at restaurants because I was in uniform were the haute cuisine of discrimination at its best. There is a lot more, but I have made my point.<br><br>
I carry guilt of the Vietnam War as survivor's guilt, and traumatic guilt. I did what I was told to the best of my ability, and broke no rules. I am guilty of no crime. I did kill the enemy. The ememy also pushed women and children into the line of fire, and made them fight as well. Things happened, as they have happened in every war since the dawn of human consciousness. <br><br>
 
